rname may have arisen as a habitational name from any of the places called Crook in Cumberland and Durham, or Crooke in Lancashire, all of which are derived from this word.","topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) barrow or mound’ from Brittonic <i>crüg</i>. In some instances this may have arisen as a habitational name from either Crook in Combe Raleigh or perhaps Crooke in North Tawton (both Devon), which are derived from this word."]},{"name":"Croston","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire named Croston, from Old Norse <i>kross</i> ‘cross’ or Old English <i>cros</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","English: occasionally, a variant of   Croxton   or   Croson  ."]}]},{"name":"Magery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Magery Croxton was born about 1055, in Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre, France. She had at least 1 son with Gilbert de Venables II. She died in 1103, in Venables, Eure, Upper Normandy, France, at the age of 49."},"et":{"Abt 1055–1103":"umbes 1055–1103","1050–1130":"1050–1130","1116–1188":"1116–1188","1055–1103":"1055–1103","1116":"1116","1103":"1103","Abt 1055":"umbes 1055","1188":"1188","1055":"1055","1130":"1130","1050":"1050","Blois, Loire-Et-Cher, Centre-Val De Loire, France":"Blois, Loir-et-Cher, Centre, Prantsusmaa","Venables, Eure, Duchy Of Normandy, France":"Venables, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1055–1103":"noin 1055–1103","1050–1130":"1050–1130","1116–1188":"1116–1188","1055–1103":"1055–1103","1116":"1116","1103":"1103","Abt 1055":"noin 1055","1188":"1188","1055":"1055","1130":"1130","1050":"1050","Blois, Loire-Et-Cher, Centre-Val De Loire, France":"Blois, Loir-et-Cher, 